### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.

First, I wanna thank you for all the awesome work you do 💪
Axios is a really nice library and makes working with http request a breeze.

I'm currently working on a project where there is a bunch of async code.
I found that you can let the user decide what to throw when a promise is cancelled by putting the `signal.reason` in the `reject` function `reject(signal.reason);`

The one who implements the async function then doesn't have to also implement a `Cancel` object that is thrown when a promise is rejected. Additionally the user can define whatever object they want to receive when cancelling a promise.

### Describe the solution you'd like

Use `reject(signal.reason)` instead of `reject(axiosSpecificValue)`.
Use `throw signal.reason` instead of `throw axiosSpecificValue`.

```typescript
// Here is an example of a delay function that throws the signal.reason inside an AbortSignal
export const delay = (milliSeconds: number, signal: AbortSignal): Promise<void> => {
	return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
		const timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
			signal.removeEventListener('abort', cleanUpTimeout);
			resolve();
		}, milliSeconds);

		const cleanUpTimeout = () => {
			clearTimeout(timeoutId);
			signal.removeEventListener('abort', cleanUpTimeout);
			reject(signal.reason); // <---------------------------- vs reject(customValue)
		};

		signal.addEventListener('abort', cleanUpTimeout);
	});
}
```

### Describe alternatives you've considered

There is an easy workaround so this is not super critical 😅 but it could potentially reduce the amount of code in axios.

```typescript
const func = async () => {
	const abortReason = 'my abort reason';
	const controller = new AbortController();
	const signal = controller.signal;
	
	setTimeout(() => controller.abort(abortReason), 1000);
	
	try {
		const response = await axio.get('/endpoints', { signal });
	}
	catch (e) {                      // possible now | possible after change
		if (signal.aborted) {    //     yes      |        yes
		if (e === abortReason) { //      no      |        yes
		if (axios.isCancel(e)) { //     yes      |        no
			return;
		}
		else {
			throw e;
		}
	}
}
