### Describe the bug

We are using the auth0 API with a React Native app and are using an interceptor to inject the auth token into the header for every request. The issue we have is that on Android (in both a simulator and on a device) the interceptor does not seem to work immediately so the first request we make is not intercepted.

We can work around this using a filthy `setTimeout` hack to delay rendering of the component making the API call for a few hundred milliseconds but that feels like a brittle workaround.

### To Reproduce

Reproducing this really needs an asynchronous API like `react-native-auth0`. Because this API is hook-based we are using a wrapper component with `useEffect` to install and remove the interceptors. While this initialisation takes place we have another state flag set to we don't render the `children` until after the interceptor is added. However, rendering immediately after installing the interceptor is where the pain lies.

We are using `@tanstack/react-query` to make API calls and as soon as our main page renders we make a call to fetch some data. It is this first call that is not intercepted. Subsequent calls later in the app flow work fine. If the API is not available and we let the query retry, then the subsequent retries are intercepted.

So here's our special component used to install the interceptor:

```tsx
function AuthGuard(props) {
  const [init, setInit] = React.useState(false);
  const auth0 = useAuth0();

  React.useEffect(() => {
    const requestInterceptor = axios.interceptors.request.use(
      async (config) => {
        // Do we have a token?
        const hasCredentials = await auth0.hasValidCredentials();
        if (hasCredentials) {
          try {
            // Get the access token from auth0
            const credentials = await auth0.getCredentials();
            // Add the access token to the request
            if (credentials) {
              config.headers.Authorization = `Bearer ${credentials.accessToken}`;
            }
          } catch (err) {
            console.log(err);
          }
        }
        return config;
      },
      (error) => Promise.reject(error)
    );    

    // Without this timeout the first request made when rendering the children on Android will not be intercepted
    setTimeout(() => {
      setInit(true);
    }, 100);

    return () => {
      setInit(false);
      axios.interceptors.request.eject(requestInterceptor);
    };
  }, [auth0]);

  return init ? props.children : null;
}
```

We then wrap our app with this component, something like this:

```tsx
export default function App() {
  return (
    <Auth0Provider
      domain="OUR_DOMAIN"
      clientId="OUR_CLIENT_ID"
    >
      <QueryClientProvider client={queryClient}>
        <AuthGuard>
          <HomeScreen />
        </AuthGuard>
      </QueryClientProvider>
    </Auth0Provider>
  );
}
```

